Assessment of a Potential Velocity Barrier for Adult Steelhead Migration on the South Fork Clearwater River - PRELIMINARY

Michael W. Ackerman1,✉, and Ryan N. Kinzer1

30 January, 2024

1 Nez Perce Tribe, Department of Fisheries Resources Management, 14054 Burr Dr., McCall, Idaho, 83638, USA

✉ Correspondence: Michael W. Ackerman <mikea@nezperce.org>

1 Background

A section of the South Fork Clearwater River near milepost (MP) 28 has been considered a potential barrier to adult steelhead migration due to high velocities, at least during particular flows. These high water velocities are hypothesized to hinder, or even prevent, some adult steelhead from migrating upstream of the barrier, limiting their use of available spawning habitat upstream of the high-velocity section in the mainsteam South Fork Clearwater River and tributaries. Namely, previous work has indicated that stream velocities within the section likely impede upstream passage for adult steelhead at flows greater than approximately 1,000 cfs (~600 cfs at the previous Elk City gage) (Timm et al., 2018, 2017).

This document provides a preliminary assessment of adult steelhead passage at the putative velocity barrier (hereafter barrier) based on detections of PIT-tagged adults in the South Fork Clearwater River, including at sites SC3 and SC4 located downstream and upstream of the barrier, respectively. In particular, we’re interested in whether PIT-tag observations suggest that adults passing SC3 “convert” to locatons upstream of the barrier (e.g., SC4) at rates lower than expected, suggesting that the barrier hinders or prevents passage at least for some adults. Although the evaluation is focused on steelhead, we include data from PIT-tagged adult Chinook salmon for comparison.

1.1 Study area

The section of the river considered to be a potential velocity barrier is located on river kilometer (rkm) 71 of the South Fork Clearwater River (Figure 1.1). Figure 1.1 and Table 1.1 additionally show each of the instream PIT tag detection sites (IPTDS) used in the evaluation to detect adult steelhead and Chinook salmon.

Figure 1.1: Map of the study area including the locations of each instream PIT tag detection system and the approximate location of the potential velocity barrier shown in red.

2 Evaluation

2.1 Data

Our evaluation used information from PIT-tagged adult steelhead and Chinook salmon detected at any IPTDS in the South Fork Clearwater River during their upstream migration to spawn. First, we queried DART to identify all PIT tags observed at Lower Granite Dam for steelhead and Chinook salmon, during spawn years 2022 and 2023, using the queryObsDART() function in the R package PITcleanr, and filtered those observations to identify any returning adult later observed at any IPTDS in the South Fork Clearwater River (Table 1.1). Note that adult detection rates on the Lower Granite Dam adult fish ladder are essentially 100%, and thus, any adult returning to the South Fork Clearwater River is expected to not be “missed”. We then used the PIT-tag lists of returning adults to the South Fork Clearwater River and queried their complete tag histories in PTAGIS which includes their mark and release information which will be important for subsequent analyses. The complete tag histories were then “compressed” and “filtered” using the compress() and filterDetections() in PITcleanr, respectively. For steelhead, we removed any detections after May 31 during the spawn year and for Chinook salmon after September 15 to avoid detections of any kelts, shed tags, etc. The compressed and filtered detections for steelhead and Chinook salmon for spawn years 2022 and 2023 are available for download here. The filtered detections were also converted to capture histories using the buildCapHist() function in PITcleanr. Finally, biological and origin (e.g., natural- versus hatchery-origin) for each tag were pulled from the Lower Granite Dam trapping database (LGTrappingDB). All data and code used in this evaluation are available at a GitHub site here.

2.2 Conversion Rates

We estimated conversion rates to each IPTDS for Chinook salmon and steelhead in spawn years 2022 and 2023 (Table 2.1). The conversion rate is an estimate of the percentage of PIT-tagged adults that arrived at a given site of those that passed the previous site. For example, in SY2022, we estimated that 12 PIT-tagged steelhead passed SC4, which is 15.6% of the 77 PIT-tagged steelhead estimated to have passed SC3. Table 2.1 provides the number of tags observed, detection efficiencies, expanded (estimated) tags and conversion rates by IPTDS site, species, and spawn year.

2.3 Length and Saltwater Age

We summarized conversion rates by fork length (mm) and saltwater age for those adults that were sampled and/or PIT-tagged at Lower Granite Dam (Tables 2.2 and 2.3). If the river section of interest was problematic to adult passage due to high water velocities, we might anticipate that conversion rates are higher for larger or older fish because of increased fitness and swimming capabilities. Sample sizes are low, but no noticeable trends were observed in conversion rates by length or saltwater age (Tables 2.2 and 2.3).

2.4 Flow

We summarized conversion rates by water level (m) recorded at SC4 using the IPTDS environmental probe (Table 2.4). It is worth noting that above a water level of 0.8 m, only 1 of 23 steelhead that passed SC3 arrived at SC4; however, sample sizes are small and nearly all Chinook salmon that passed SC3 arrived at SC4 at similar water levels. For this summary, the water level recorded for each fish was the water level at SC4 when that fish was most recently seen at SC3, SC2, or SC1.

2.5 Release Group

We also considered release groups when evaluating conversion or passage rates through the high-velocity section; adults that return from juvenile releases downstream of the reach may not have the propensity to migrate through the reach. Table @ref(tab:release groups) shows that among adult Chinook salmon and steelhead returning to the South Fork Clearwater River in spawn years 2022 and 2023, only 22 steelhead were from a juvenile release upstream near Newsome Creek (NEWSOC). Of those 22 steelhead, 3 were observed migrating through the high-velocity reach and arrived at SC4 (Table 2.7).

3 Discussion

Based on adult returns in spawn years 2022 and 2023, it is difficult to discern whether the high-velocity reach hinders or prevents upstream passage for steelhead. Conversion rates to SC4 from SC3 were 13.9% and 15.6% for adult in spawn years 2022 and 2023, respectively; however, those rates are not considerable different that conversion rates of 29.3% and 13.4% to SC3 from SC2 (Table 2.1). Very few adult steelhead were observed migrating to SC4 during higher flows (Table 2.5), but sample sizes are low. Moreover, very few adults from juvenile releases upstream of the high-velocity reach were available for our evaluation.

Juvenile steelhead were released in Newsome Creek in spring 2022; 1-ocean adults from those releases will return to the South Fork Clearwater River in spring 2024 and 2-ocean adults in spring 2025. Those returning adults should provide a more thorough evaluation of passage through the high-velocity reach.
